  "created": "2025-10-15",
  "description": "The Target of Rapamycin (TOR) pathway in S. cerevisiae is the master regulator of cell growth in response to nutrient availability. TOR exists in two complexes: TORC1 (Tor1 or Tor2 with Kog1, Lst8, Tco89) senses amino acids, nitrogen, and glucose to promote anabolic processes; TORC2 (Tor2 with Avo1-3, Bit61, Lst8) regulates actin cytoskeleton and ceramide synthesis. TORC1 activation promotes ribosome biogenesis, protein synthesis, and nutrient import while repressing autophagy, stress responses, and catabolic processes. Under nutrient limitation or rapamycin treatment, TORC1 is inhibited, leading to Tap42-Sit4 phosphatase activation, Gcn2-mediated translational control, and Msn2/4-dependent stress gene expression. The pathway integrates signals from amino acids (via EGO complex), nitrogen (via Gtr1/2), and glucose (via PKA cross-talk). This flowchart illustrates TORC1 activation, downstream effectors, nutrient sensing mechanisms, and the growth-to-quiescence transition.",
  "id": "yeast_tor_signaling",
