  "name": "TOR Signaling Pathway (Nutrient Sensing)",
  "notGates": 15,
  "notes": "TOR was discovered in yeast through genetic screens for rapamycin resistance, making S. cerevisiae the model for understanding this conserved pathway. TORC1 is the nutrient-responsive complex (rapamycin-sensitive) while TORC2 regulates cytoskeleton. TOR integrates multiple nutrient signals (amino acids via EGO, nitrogen via Gln3, glucose via PKA) to control the growth-quiescence decision. The pathway is highly conserved: mammalian mTOR has identical functions in cancer, aging, and metabolism. TOR inhibition by rapamycin or nutrient starvation extends lifespan in yeast and other organisms. This pathway exemplifies eukaryotic signal integration with multiple AND gates for complex assembly and signal coordination.",
  "organism": "S. cerevisiae",
  "relatedProcesses": [
    "yeast_autophagy",
    "yeast_gcn4_amino_acid_starvation",
    "yeast_pka_pathway",
    "yeast_ribosome_biogenesis"
  ],
  "scientificAccuracy": "This flowchart is based on decades of research on TOR signaling in yeast, the model organism for TOR discovery. All components (TOR complexes, Tap42, Sit4, Sch9, EGO complex), regulatory mechanisms, and downstream targets have been extensively validated and are highly conserved in mammals (mTOR). The model represents how eukaryotic cells couple growth to nutrient availability.",
